note.body: Done. Please re-review.

> Is this really necessary?

Yes, it is necessary. If you're not willing to do the work, then that means that it will eat into the time I, or somebody else, has for this type of work.

Is this really necessary? All of these three plugins are awfully outdated and were broken for a quite long time, causing Totem (and other apps using grilo) to crash in most cases. The Apple Trailers plugin is also unfixable because the original service is no longer available. The other two are probably fixable, but it would require a lot of time and effort to actually fix them. Are you interested in doing this? I am not aware of any effort to actually do this other than [this MR](https://gitlab.gnome.org/GNOME/grilo/-/merge_requests/101) (still unmerged, by the way) from Sid that prevents crash in the Rai.tv plugin (but does not make it working).

There is also a problem that the Apple Trailers and Euronews plugins cannot be disabled at build time (without patching the `src/lua-factory/sources/meson.build` file). Releasing a new version of grilo-plugins with such broken plugins that are always on is not a good idea in my opinion.

note.body: So is there any conclusion? There is no point in keeping these plugins in such broken state. They should either be fixed or removed. And as Sid pointed out, there is probably not much point in fixing them.

### My thoughts (based on my limited understanding):

From what I understand, Apple Trailers have been moved to AppleTV and there is no good way to get Apple Trailers anymore. So, I think Apple Trailers can be removed. Not entirely sure about euronews and raitv. 

On a more general note, over the past years I found only Apple Trailers a bit useful when it worked in Totem. I didn't use / understand much of Euronews and Raitv, as its content was neither useful / interesting nor does it cater to international audience. That raises the question of whether grilo network plugins have much use in 2024. In the sense, do we have good content providers who have a stable open/free API which a grilo network plugin can query and provide to clients like totem. We don't want to parse content (HTML etc), which is always known to break with small changes to HTML tags and with the limited maintenance time of grilo / grilo-plugins, this (parsing HTML) is never going to reliably serve any use case.

The general trend in 2024 is more like: if there is a good content provider API, it's probably a paid service (N API requests per $$). No one in 2024 wants to provide good content API free of cost to be monetized by someone else. AppleTV is an example of that. I heard `'tvdb'` being used by some projects. Maybe, there are more like `tvdb` in 2024. I don't know.

Thanks!
